%N A391109 Number of ways to write 2*n as p + p' + 2^a + 2^b, where p and p' > p are consecutive primes, and a and b are positive integers with a <= b.
%C A391109 a(n) = 0 for no 5 < n <= 4*10^5. a(n) = 1 for n = 6, 7, 3847, 4507, 4293, 14372, 29477, 29803, 164437, 181627, 186871, 195617, 233287, 336967.
%C A391109 After learning the author's question whether a(n) > 0 for all n > 5. Dr. Hui-Xi Li at Nankai Univ. and Prof. Qing-Hu Hou at Tianjin Univ. found that 449233 and 4036496 are the first and the second values of n > 5 with a(n) = 0, respectively.
%H A391109 Zhi-Wei Sun, <a href="/A391109/b391109.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%e A391109 a(6) = 1 since 2*6 = 3 + 5 + 2 + 2 with 3 and 5 consecutive primes.
%e A391109 a(29803) = 1 since 2*29803 = 13417 + 13421 + 2^14 + 2^14 with 13417 and 13421 consecutive primes.
%e A391109 a(195617) = 1 since 2*195617 = 190997 + 191021 + 2^10 + 2^13 with 190997 and 191021 consecutive primes.
%e A391109 a(233287) = 1 since 2*233287 = 233143 + 233159 + 2^4 + 2^8 with 233143 and 233159 consecutive primes.
%t A391109 p[n_]:=p[n]=Prime[n]; S[n_]:=S[n]=p[n]+p[n+1];
%t A391109 f[n_]:=f[n]=Sum[If[S[k]<=n&&S[k+1]>n,k,0],{k,1,PrimePi[n/2]}];
%t A391109 YQ[n_]:=YQ[n]=(n>4&&S[f[n]]==n);
%t A391109 tab={};Do[m=0;Do[If[YQ[2n-2^a-2^b],m=m+1],{a,1,Log[2,n]},{b,a,Log[2,2n-2^a]}];tab=Append[tab,m],{n,1,100}];Print[tab]
